properties.Acoustic_Summary: Bar BC Ranch is a sage brush dominated location on the banks of the Snake River. The rapids on the Snake River are generally audible. Wind picks up in the summer afternoons along with insect activity. Birds are also frequently heard. This area is directly under the flight path of aircraft approaching the Jackson Hole Airport from the north.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in burnt pines; photo looking south
properties.Photo2_Caption: Site in burnt pines; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: At this backcountry site natural sounds predominate. Distant rushing water flowing out of the Teton Mountain Range can be heard during calm periods and wind in the trees is a common sound. Aircraft noise from the Jackson Hole Airport can often be heard from the southeast, and occasional sounds of human-activity can be heard from the nearby park housing area.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in regenerating pines; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Adjacent to residential housing, sounds from building utilities and people activity were often heard. At night natural sounds predominated.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in residential area; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Only three windy winter days were sampled at this early monitoring site in the sage brush flats south of Blacktail Butte. Vehicles on the Gros Ventre Road and aircraft flying overhead and at the Jackson Hole Airport were audible. See nearby GRTEGVCE for more details of this general area.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in swale south of Blacktail Butte; photo looking northwest

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Sampling at this site spanned winter and spring. The site was in the backyard of the historic Brinkerhoff House in an aspen grove near the shore of Jackson Lake. At night and during calm periods silence predominated, especially during the winter.
properties.All_Hours: Silence (48%), All non-natural sounds (35%), All natural sources (24%), Unknown motor sounds (14%), Wind (11%), People (9%), Road vehicles (6%), Bird (8%), Aircraft (8%), Mammals (4%), Snow plows (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site near shore; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: This winter site was located near the snowmobile access point for Jackson Lake and in a small stand of aspens on the lakeshore. Along with winter silence, sounds included snowmobiles and sounds from road vehicles. See nearby GRTECBPA for more details of the soundscape of this general area
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site at edge of Jackson Lake in trees; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: This site collected data from late winter into spring. Silence was the most predominant ‘sound’, but wind and people's voices during the day were often heard.
properties.All_Hours: Silence (33%), All natural sources (30%), All non-natural sounds (29%), Wind (21%), People (11%), Unknown motor sounds (8%),  Bird (7%), Aircraft (7%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site under tree near summer picnic area; photo looking northwest

properties.Acoustic_Summary: One of the earliest monitoring sites in Grand Teton, data were collected for only four days. The monitor was only a few feet from the end of the lake access road so the loudest sounds were from the occasion vehicles using the road. When calm and especially at night, the area was very quiet.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site just off turnaround loop; photo looking north

properties.Acoustic_Summary: The rushing waters of Cascade Creek dominated the soundscape of this narrow canyon. The flowing water sounds were loud enough to obscure most distant or quiet sounds. Birds were the only other sound source audible for more than 10% of the time.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sources (100%), Flowing water (100%), Bird (19%), All non-natural sounds (5%), Insect (4%), Aircraft (3%), People (2%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site next to large glacial erratic; photo looking northeast

properties.Acoustic_Summary: As one of the earliest monitoring sites in Grand Teton, data were collected for only five days. The monitor was hundred feet from the main road so other than a low-flying propeller plane, the loudest sounds were from the vehicles using the road.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site 100 feet from road; photo looking southwest

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Adjacent to the occasionally groomed Grassy Lake Road, this site collected data for 12 days during the winter. This very quiet soundscape was occasionally interupted by nearby snowmobiles and high flying jets.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site down the trail in thick forest; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: The sounds of this site include distant motors including road vehicles and oversnow vehicles in and around Flagg Ranch. Silence was common followed by the sound of wind in the trees.
properties.All_Hours: All non-natural sources (24%), All natural sources (54%), Silence (29%), Wind (12%), Unknown motor (11%), Aircraft (7%), Bird (4%), All oversnow vehicles (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site at edge of large meadow; photo looking east-southeast

properties.Acoustic_Summary: On the roof of an office trailer at park headquarters, non-natural sounds dominated this site. However, surprisingly the sounds of birds and flowing water joined with wind and rain as common natural sound sources.
properties.All_Hours: All non-natural sounds (92%), All natural sources (67%), Road vehicles (52%), Building utilities (48%), Bird (31%), Wind (23%), Flowing water (21%), Snowfall or rain (16%), People (7%), Aircraft (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site on office trailer; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Located in an area of sage brush and grasses, it was only the tangle of downed tree trunks that kept bison from coming close to the equipment. Bison grunts were often heard along with wind, birds, and insects. Distant road vehicles and aircraft were also regularly audible.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sources (90%), Wind (54%), All non-natural sounds (42%), Bird (34%), Insect (32%), Road vehicles (20%), Aircraft (14%), Mammal (13%), Rain (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in deadfall; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Adjacent to a small stream, the soundscape ws dominated by the sounds of flowing water. Birds and the sounds from the Jenny Lake Boating shuttle were also frequent sounds sources.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sources (100%), Flowing water (96%), All non-natural sounds (34%), Bird (30%), Watercraft (26%), Wind (6%), Mammal (4%), Unknown motor (4%), Aircraft (3%), Insect (2%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in forest; photo looking south

properties.Acoustic_Summary: This site was in an unusual site location at the north end of the Jackson Hole Runway near a Sage Grouse lek. As expected birds, not only Sage Grouse, were regularly heard along with wind and aircraft. Many of the unidentified motor sounds were from ground operations of the airport but also road vehicles on the highway.
properties.All_Hours: All non-natural sounds (87%), All natural sources (69%), Unknown motor (56%), Bird (48%), Wind (32%), Aircraft (22%), Road vehicles (15%), Rain (5%), Insect (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site near approach landing lights; photo looking east
properties.Photo2_Caption: Site near north end of runway; photo looking south

properties.Acoustic_Summary: The monitoring equipment at this site collected only digital recordings that were then processed to estimate sound levels. Snow was still deep at the beginning of the sampling period, but visitor activity increased during the month. Silence was still the most common ‘sound’
properties.All_Hours: Silence (62%), All natural sounds (26%), All non-natural sounds (13%), Wind (12%), Waves (9%), Helicopter (5%), All aircraft (5%), Bird (4%), All watercraft (2%)

properties.Acoustic_Summary: This site was on a small island just off of Leek's Mariina throughout all the seasons. Birds, waves, wind and silence were the most common sounds heard. Motorboats, aircraft, and unidentified motors were heard regularly.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sounds (70%), All non-natural sounds (34%), Birds (31%), Waves (29%), Wind (20%), Silence (19%), Unknown motor sounds (13%), Watercraft (10%), Aircraft (6%), Road vehicles (4%), Snowfall or rain (3%), People’s Voices (3%), Insects (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site at edge of water; photo looking southwest
properties.Photo2_Caption: Site at edge of lake; photo looking southwest

properties.Acoustic_Summary: This site, installed primarily to measure aircraft sounds in late winter, had wind as the most common sound source followed by silence and distant road vehicles.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sounds (73%), Wind (59%), All non-natural sounds (29%), Silence (16%), Road vehicles (14%), Birds (10%), All aircraft (9%), Rain (8%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in pines; photo looking west

properties.Acoustic_Summary: This very early monitoring site was one of the quietest. Wind and silence dominate the depth of winter soundscape. Occasional bird and red squirrels are also audible.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site near lake; photo looking south

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Located on the west shore of frozen Jackson Lake, natural sounds dominated this area. Wind, birds, and silence were the most common sounds. Aircraft, snowplows, and unidentified motor sounds carried across the lake from the east side. Snowmobiles on the lake were heard, but very infrequently.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sounds (63%), Wind (36%), Silence (27%), Bird (20%), All non-natural sounds (18%), Snowfall ((9%), All aircraft (8%), Unknown motors (5%), Rotary snow plow (4%), Snowmbile (1%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site at base of small pine; photo looking northeast

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Placed in a high rocky pass in the mountains this site was very windy. Voices from the nearby climbers' camping area were heard during almost all hours from very early morning until after dark.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sounds (72%), All non-natural sounds (61%), Wind (60%), People's voices (52%), Birds (20%), All aircraft (9%), Insects (4%), Silence (3%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Photo from site looking north

properties.Acoustic_Summary: The soundscape at this site near a long-abandoned sage grouse lek was dominated by wind, the nearby highway and Jackson Hole Airport.
properties.Photo1_Caption: Site in sage brush; photo looking northwest
properties.Photo2_Caption: During site visit; photo of sound monitoring system

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Acoustic data was collected at this site in early and late summer. Water cascading out of the mountains was audible the majority of the time. Birds and wind were often heard. During the day voices from hikers and the Jenny Lake Boat Shuttle were audible. Aircraft and distant road traffic was occasionally heard.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sounds (97%), Flowing water (67%), Birds (65%), All non-natural sounds (33%), Wind (21%), Aircraft (11%), Mammals (7%), Watercraft (6%), Unknown motor sounds (5%), Rain (4%), Road vehicles (4%)
properties.Photo1_Caption: Photo near site looking north

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Early in the summer the rushing waters of the Snake River dominated the soundscape along with bird songs and squirrel calls. Aircraft and unidentified motors were regularly audible throughout the sampling period.
properties.All_Hours: All natural sounds (97%), Bird (61%), All non-natural sounds (60%), Flowing water (59%), Squirrel (32%), Unknown motors (32%), All aircraft (26%), Wind ((16%), Insect (16%)

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Data were collected at this site during two winter seasons. The monitor was behind the Ranger Station near the main road. The main activity was people coming or going from Yellowstone NP on their trip by oversnow vehicle. Silence and wind were the most common natural sounds

properties.Acoustic_Summary: Sounds that characterize Moose Wilson Road 3 include wind and the near and distant sounds of motors originating from the Jackson Hole Airport and road vehicles. During the winter when the adjacent section of the Moose Wilson Road is plowed, but not heavily used, road vehicles are heard regularly. In the summer the nearby road dominates the soundscape during the day. Birds sing and red squirrels chatter, and in the autumn the forest echoes with the sounds of elk bugling.
